From 69de3075adbc46a2ee0ef561574302c7d0736aae Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: ak2k <19240940+ak2k@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Sat, 18 Apr 2026 10:48:24 -0400
Subject: [PATCH 2/2] libstore: Harden darwin Mach-O fixup for fat64, dual-CD,
 CMS cases
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The parent commit threw on fat64 detection and skipped SHA-1
CodeDirectories. Two real-world classes of nixpkgs binary
remained broken:

  * fat64 containers (emitted by `lipo -create -fat64`).
  * Binaries with dual-CD SuperBlobs — pre-2016 SHA-1 + SHA-256
    alternates that some nixpkgs dylibs still carry (e.g.
    some .NET universal dylibs). The kernel validates every CD
    at page-in, so leaving SHA-1 slots stale still SIGKILLs the
    binary at load.

This commit walks `fat_arch_64` entries and recomputes per-CD
slots using the CD's own hash algorithm.

A third class cannot be repaired in place. Binaries carrying
an embedded CMS signature whose PKCS#7 payload chains off the
CodeDirectory's hash (Developer ID / App Store) would need the
original signing identity to be re-signed after any page-hash
recompute, since the CMS blob commits to the CD's cdhash. The
fixup detects a non-empty `CSMAGIC_BLOBWRAPPER` under
`CSSLOT_SIGNATURESLOT` (0x10000) and skips those slices with a
warning. Observed on binaries whose upstream Developer ID
signature the nixpkgs wrapper build does not re-link away.

Three bounds checks reject malformed inputs early (all return 0):

  * `maxNFatArch = 16` rejects Java `.class` files, which share
    the `0xcafebabe` magic with fat32.
  * `validSliceBounds` uses `size > fileSize - offset` so u64
    values from a fat64 header can't wrap.
  * `maxSuperBlobCount = 16` caps the CodeDirectory-iteration
    loop.

Test coverage extends to fat32 (1-arch + multi-arch), fat64
dylib, self-reference, codesign-signed, symlink, malformed
fat-header adversarials, and a synthetic CMS-signed binary.
The CMS fixture asserts `codesign --verify` reports "code or
signature have been modified" post-`RewritingSink` — the error
that proves the helper left stale page hashes in place. A
helper that wrongly recomputed slots would produce a different
codesign error that a bare exit-code check would mask. fat64
slices are verified via `lipo -thin` + `codesign --verify`
because Apple's `codesign` does not parse fat64 directly on
macOS 26.
